text: I look at this and I agree with you. I doubt, although I hope I'm wrong, that this is the last pandemic that we see. I'm not even sure it's the last COVID-19 occurrence that we're going to see. What I think is more interesting is really around the response. You think about a monetary and fiscal response. And so how is that going to change? We saw in the global financial crisis, there was a ton of pushback on the Fed and Treasury for the stimulus that they did. The first TARP bill got shot down and then the second one passed and immediately it was, well, that wasn't even close to big enough. It's just getting people used to trillion dollars or whatever it was. I remember I kept it in like the 950 billion range because nobody wanted that T number out there. And now here we are 10 years later and we're into, you know, 2 trillion, 4 trillion, 6 trillion. Some people, if you annualize it, will say, well, it's 20 trillion. Whatever the number is, these are big, big numbers. And so what I think is more interesting is now the response has become something bad happens and we need stimulus. And every time we give stimulus, it seems like it becomes easier to give more stimulus. What is the ramifications of that? If you're on the MMT side of the argument, you would say, of course, and we should have low unemployment. The government should ensure low unemployment. And infrastructure projects. Yeah. And all of that. Maybe that's right. Again, I'm not in the business of trying to think about what's right or wrong from a social perspective. I have my opinions and that's a different conversation. But if that is the case, what does that mean for asset prices? On the other side, you have the dollar bulls who might say, look, the dollar keeps getting stronger against all of the currencies. What's that going to do to non-US dollar denominated debt? Does this turn into a solvency crisis? What does that mean for markets? So those are like extracting away from COVID or whatever, which the next thing was housing last time. It's COVID this time. The responses are the same. It's the same playbook, just bigger. And so what does that mean? If every crisis is going to be more stimulus, what does that mean for asset prices? You can very quickly create a story for a V-shaped recovery in higher markets or higher S&P, I should say, with a lot of stimulus.
